We use the central limit formulas for a random mean. \[\mu_{\bar{X}} = \mu_{X} = 76.53 \] \[\sigma_{\bar{X}} = \frac{\sigma_{X}}{\sqrt{n}} = \frac{8.95}{\sqrt{97}} = 0.9087348\] So, we think the random mean is normally distributed with a mean of 76.53 and a standard deviation of 0.9087348. \[\bar{X} \sim N(76.53,\,0.9087348) \]

Calculate a \(z\)-score for the boundary. \[z = \frac{0.77}{0.9087348} = 0.8473319 \]

You can round that to \(z=0.84\) or \(z=0.85\). Any of the following probabilities will get credit. \[P(|Z| > 0.8473319) = 0.3968102 \] \[P(|Z| > 0.84) = 0.401 \] \[P(|Z| > 0.85) = 0.3954 \]
